// Grammar for the *contextual-lexer* error-recovery oracle (issue #166).
//
// AWORD and BWORD share the SAME pattern (`/[a-z]+/`) but are distinct terminals,
// each valid only in a distinct parser state: AWORD inside `[...]`, BWORD inside
// `{...}`. The basic/global lexer compiles them together, so its tie-break retypes
// EVERY word to one of them — BWORD then never matches and a `[...] {...}` input
// can't parse at all. The contextual lexer narrows by parser state and types each
// word correctly, so recovery over the contextual stream (with the root-lexer
// fallback) reaches the same tree a clean contextual parse would build.
//
// This is the load-bearing-contextual-lexer case #166 is about: recovery must lex
// contextually, not with a stored basic lexer. The two recovery branches both fire
// in the test cases: a stray `}` inside `[...]` is an out-of-context-but-valid
// token (root lexer matches it -> deletable), and a stray digit is un-lexable even
// by the root set (-> one-character skip).
start: a_part b_part
a_part: "[" AWORD+ "]"
b_part: "{" BWORD+ "}"
AWORD: /[a-z]+/
BWORD: /[a-z]+/
%ignore " "
